==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|halou|lang=enm}}, {{term|halow|lang=enm}}, {{term|halloo||pos=interjection used to call attention|lang=enm}}, representing {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|hēlā}}, {{m|ang|ǣlā}}, {{m|ang|ēalā||O!, alas!, oh!, lo!}}, equivalent to {{compound|hey|lo|lang=en}}.

===Interjection===
{{en-interj}}

# A variant of '''[[hello]]'''
# A cry of [[surprise]].
#* '''1890''', [[w:Sir Arthur Conan Doyle|Sir Arthur Conan Doyle]], ''[[s:The Sign of the Four|The Sign of the Four]]'',
#*: It sounds like a sum in the rule of three. The answer should give us the — But '''hallo'''! here are the accredited representatives of the law.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The cry "hallo!"
# A shout of exultation.

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To shout, or to call with a loud voice.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To chase while shouting "hallo!"
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To cry "hallo" (to someone).
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To shout (something).

